Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant is not to share, reproduce or distribute any personal and/or identifying information about the crime victim(s), except to their attorney.  Defendant is not to apply or renew his passport and if he were to he needs to surrender his passport to the Waukesha Criminal Traffic Office (Room C226).  Defendant is not to possess or view any pornographic material.  Defendant is not to be within 1000 feet of any school or child care facility.  Absolute sobriety, defendant is not to possess or consume any alcohol.  Defendant is not to use/possess any controlled substances without a valid prescription and take as prescribed.  Defendant is not to possess any dangerous weapons/firearms.  The Court will give the defendant until 2:00 PM to get his personal belongings from his daughter's residence.  Defendant to comply with GPS monitoring through Wisconsin Community Services.  Defendant is to report to WCS immediately after Court today.  Defendant is not to access social media.  The Court will allow for the defendant to use electronic devices for the purposes of work.
